{
  "The basic contractile unit of skeletal muscle is the:": "",
  "Sarcomere": "",
  "Fascicle": "",
  "Muscle fiber": "",
  "Myofibril": "",
  "The sarcomere is the smallest functional contractile unit of a muscle fiber, extending from one Z line to the next and containing the organized actin and myosin filaments responsible for contraction.": "",
  "The correct structural hierarchy from largest to smallest in skeletal muscle is:": "",
  "Muscle, Fascicle, Fiber, Myofibril, Sarcomere": "",
  "Sarcomere, Myofibril, Fiber, Fascicle, Muscle": "",
  "Myofibril, Fiber, Muscle, Fascicle, Sarcomere": "",
  "Fiber, Fascicle, Muscle, Sarcomere, Myofibril": "",
  "The organizational hierarchy runs from the whole muscle down to fascicles (bundles of fibers), individual muscle fibers (cells), myofibrils (contractile strands within each fiber), and finally sarcomeres (the repeating units within myofibrils).": "",
  "The sarcoplasmic reticulum in a muscle fiber stores:": "",
  "ATP molecules": "",
  "Glycogen granules": "",
  "Sodium ions": "",
  "Calcium ions (Ca2+)": "",
  "The sarcoplasmic reticulum (SR) is a specialized smooth endoplasmic reticulum in muscle fibers that sequesters and releases calcium ions, which are essential for initiating the contraction cycle.": "",
  "Which connective tissue layer wraps around a single muscle fiber?": "",
  "Deep fascia": "",
  "Epimysium": "",
  "Perimysium": "",
  "Endomysium": "",
  "The endomysium is the thin connective tissue sheath that surrounds each individual muscle fiber, providing structural support and carrying capillaries and nerve fibers to the cell.": "",
  "Perimysium surrounds which structure?": "",
  "A single muscle fiber": "",
  "A single sarcomere": "",
  "The entire muscle": "",
  "A fascicle (bundle of muscle fibers)": "",
  "The perimysium is a connective tissue sheath that wraps around each fascicle, which is a bundle of muscle fibers grouped together, and it carries the larger blood vessels and nerves that supply the fascicle.": "",
  "The epimysium is the connective tissue that surrounds:": "",
  "A fascicle": "",
  "A single myofibril": "",
  "The epimysium is the dense, irregular connective tissue layer that encases the entire muscle, separating it from surrounding tissues and organs while also being continuous with tendons at the muscle's ends.": "",
  "At the neuromuscular junction (NMJ), the neurotransmitter released is:": "",
  "Dopamine": "",
  "Epinephrine": "",
  "Serotonin": "",
  "Acetylcholine (ACh)": "",
  "Acetylcholine is the specific neurotransmitter used at all neuromuscular junctions between somatic motor neurons and skeletal muscle fibers, binding to nicotinic receptors on the motor end plate to trigger muscle contraction.": "",
  "T-tubules in skeletal muscle function to:": "",
  "Store calcium ions for contraction": "",
  "Produce ATP for energy": "",
  "Remove metabolic waste products": "",
  "Conduct the action potential deep into the interior of the muscle fiber": "",
  "Transverse tubules (T-tubules) are invaginations of the sarcolemma that extend deep into the muscle fiber, ensuring that the action potential reaches the interior of the cell quickly so that all myofibrils contract nearly simultaneously.": "",
  "ACh binds to receptors located on the:": "",
  "Nerve terminal membrane": "",
  "Sarcoplasmic reticulum": "",
  "Myofibril surface": "",
  "Sarcolemma at the motor end plate": "",
  "Acetylcholine crosses the synaptic cleft and binds to nicotinic receptors concentrated on the junctional folds of the motor end plate, a specialized region of the sarcolemma (muscle cell membrane).": "",
  "A motor unit consists of:": "",
  "The entire somatic nervous system": "",
  "A single sarcomere and its Z lines": "",
  "One entire muscle and its blood supply": "",
  "One motor neuron and all the muscle fibers it innervates": "",
  "A motor unit is the functional unit of motor control, comprising a single motor neuron and every muscle fiber it innervates; when the neuron fires, all fibers in that motor unit contract together.": "",
  "What is the sarcolemma?": "",
  "The contractile protein within sarcomeres": "",
  "The plasma membrane of a muscle fiber": "",
  "The connective tissue wrapping a fascicle": "",
  "The cytoplasm of a muscle fiber": "",
  "The sarcolemma is the specialized plasma membrane of a muscle fiber (cell), which receives action potentials at the motor end plate and transmits them along the surface and into T-tubules to initiate contraction.": "",
  "What is a myofibril?": "",
  "A long, thread-like contractile organelle within a muscle fiber, composed of repeating sarcomeres": "",
  "The connective tissue sheath around the entire muscle": "",
  "The nerve fiber that stimulates a muscle": "",
  "A bundle of muscle fibers wrapped in perimysium": "",
  "A myofibril is a cylindrical organelle running the length of a muscle fiber, composed of thousands of sarcomeres arranged end-to-end; each muscle fiber contains hundreds to thousands of myofibrils that produce the actual force of contraction.": "",
  "What is the neuromuscular junction (NMJ)?": "",
  "The place where two bones meet to form a joint": "",
  "The gap junction between two cardiac muscle cells": "",
  "The synapse between the axon terminal of a motor neuron and the motor end plate of a skeletal muscle fiber": "",
  "The junction between two adjacent sarcomeres": "",
  "The neuromuscular junction is the specialized chemical synapse where a motor neuron's axon terminal communicates with a skeletal muscle fiber via the release of acetylcholine, converting a neural signal into a muscular response.": "",
  "What is the motor end plate?": "",
  "The specialized region of the sarcolemma containing a high concentration of ACh receptors at the NMJ": "",
  "The tip of the motor neuron where neurotransmitters are synthesized": "",
  "A plate of connective tissue attaching muscle to bone": "",
  "The Z line at the end of each sarcomere": "",
  "The motor end plate is the folded region of the muscle fiber's sarcolemma directly opposite the motor neuron terminal, densely packed with nicotinic acetylcholine receptors that allow the muscle to respond rapidly to neural signals.": "",
  "What is acetylcholinesterase?": "",
  "A calcium pump in the sarcoplasmic reticulum": "",
  "An enzyme in the synaptic cleft that rapidly breaks down acetylcholine to terminate the signal": "",
  "A receptor protein on the sarcolemma that binds ACh": "",
  "An enzyme that produces acetylcholine in the nerve terminal": "",
  "Acetylcholinesterase is an enzyme bound to the basal lamina in the synaptic cleft that rapidly hydrolyzes acetylcholine into acetate and choline, ensuring that each nerve impulse produces only one brief muscle response and preventing continuous stimulation.": "",
  "What does the 'all-or-none' principle mean in muscle physiology?": "",
  "Muscles can only contract to 50% of their maximum force": "",
  "A single muscle fiber either contracts fully or not at all once the stimulus reaches threshold": "",
  "All motor units in a muscle must fire simultaneously": "",
  "Every muscle in the body contracts at the same time": "",
  "The all-or-none principle states that individual muscle fibers do not produce graded contractions; once threshold depolarization is reached, the fiber contracts maximally, and force gradation in whole muscles is achieved by recruiting different numbers of motor units.": "",
  "What is the A band of a sarcomere?": "",
  "The central bare zone containing only titin proteins": "",
  "The dark band spanning the entire length of the thick (myosin) filaments, including zones of overlap with actin": "",
  "The region containing only thin (actin) filaments with no overlap": "",
  "The boundary line between two adjacent sarcomeres": "",
  "The A band is the dark-staining region of a sarcomere that corresponds to the full length of the thick myosin filaments, including the zones where thin actin filaments overlap with myosin; importantly, the A band does not change in length during contraction.": "",
  "What is the I band?": "",
  "The region where both actin and myosin fully overlap": "",
  "The boundary between two fascicles": "",
  "The region containing only thin (actin) filaments with no myosin overlap": "",
  "The region containing only thick (myosin) filaments": "",
  "The I band is the light-staining region of a sarcomere containing only thin (actin) filaments with no overlap by thick (myosin) filaments; it spans two adjacent sarcomeres and is bisected by the Z line.": "",
  "What is the H zone?": "",
  "The connective tissue layer between fascicles": "",
  "Another name for the Z line": "",
  "The region at each end of the sarcomere where only actin filaments are present": "",
  "The central region of the A band containing only thick (myosin) filaments with no actin overlap": "",
  "The H zone is the lighter central portion of the A band where only thick myosin filaments are present and no thin actin filaments reach; during contraction, the H zone narrows and can disappear completely.": "",
  "What are Z lines (Z discs)?": "",
  "Regions of myosin-only filaments in the center of the sarcomere": "",
  "Protein structures that define the boundaries of each sarcomere and anchor the thin (actin) filaments": "",
  "The motor end plates at the neuromuscular junction": "",
  "Calcium storage sites within the sarcoplasmic reticulum": "",
  "Z lines (or Z discs) are dense protein structures that mark the lateral boundaries of each sarcomere, anchoring the actin thin filaments and connecting adjacent sarcomeres end-to-end along the length of the myofibril.": "",
  "A physical therapist is working with a patient who has difficulty making precise eye movements after a stroke. The therapist explains that eye muscles have very small motor units. Why would small motor units be important for eye movements?": "",
  "Small motor units fatigue less quickly than large motor units": "",
  "Small motor units allow finer, more precise control of movement because each neuron controls only a few muscle fibers": "",
  "Small motor units generate more total force than large motor units": "",
  "Small motor units are only found in the legs, not the eyes": "",
  "Small motor units, where one neuron innervates only a few muscle fibers, allow very fine gradations of force and precise movements, which is essential for delicate tasks like tracking objects with the eyes or threading a needle.": "",
  "A nursing student is preparing an intramuscular injection into a patient's deltoid muscle. She must insert the needle through several tissue layers. In which order would the needle pass through the connective tissue coverings from outside to inside?": "",
  "Endomysium, then epimysium, then perimysium": "",
  "Epimysium, then perimysium, then endomysium": "",
  "Perimysium, then epimysium, then endomysium": "",
  "Endomysium, then perimysium, then epimysium": "",
  "From the outside in, the needle would first penetrate the epimysium (covering the whole muscle), then the perimysium (covering a fascicle), and finally the endomysium (covering individual muscle fibers), reflecting the nested hierarchy of muscle connective tissue.": "",
  "A researcher is studying a patient with a genetic defect that prevents the sarcoplasmic reticulum from releasing calcium ions. What would be the expected effect on the patient's skeletal muscles?": "",
  "The muscles would be in a state of constant contraction": "",
  "The muscles would contract normally but tire more quickly": "",
  "The muscles would grow larger due to compensatory mechanisms": "",
  "The muscles would be unable to contract because calcium cannot bind troponin to expose actin binding sites": "",
  "Without calcium release from the SR, troponin cannot undergo its conformational change, tropomyosin remains blocking the actin binding sites, and myosin heads cannot form cross-bridges, resulting in the inability of the muscle to contract.": "",
  "During a laboratory practical, a student examines a sarcomere diagram and notices that after contraction, the I band and H zone have narrowed but the A band remains the same width. Which principle of muscle contraction does this observation support?": "",
  "The myosin filaments dissolve during contraction": "",
  "The sliding filament theory, where thin filaments slide past thick filaments without either changing length": "",
  "The muscle fibers themselves physically shorten by breaking apart": "",
  "The Z lines move farther apart during contraction": "",
  "The sliding filament theory predicts that the A band (length of myosin) stays constant while the I band and H zone narrow because actin slides inward over myosin, bringing Z lines closer together without any filament changing its own length.": "",
  "A patient is given a drug that blocks acetylcholinesterase at the neuromuscular junction. What would you expect to happen to the patient's skeletal muscles?": "",
  "The muscles would contract normally with no observable changes": "",
  "The muscles would only contract during sleep": "",
  "The muscles would experience prolonged contraction and possible spasms because ACh is not being broken down": "",
  "The muscles would become paralyzed and unable to contract": "",
  "If acetylcholinesterase is inhibited, acetylcholine accumulates in the synaptic cleft and continues to stimulate the muscle fiber, causing prolonged depolarization, sustained contraction, and potential muscle spasms or fasciculations.": "",
  "A anatomy professor asks a student to explain why the heart can contract continuously for decades without significant fatigue. The student should emphasize which cellular feature of cardiac muscle fibers?": "",
  "Cardiac fibers are multinucleated, giving them extra DNA for protein production": "",
  "Cardiac fibers lack sarcomeres and therefore use less energy": "",
  "Cardiac fibers are extraordinarily rich in mitochondria, occupying about 25% of cell volume, providing continuous aerobic ATP production": "",
  "Cardiac fibers have very few mitochondria and rely on anaerobic glycolysis": "",
  "Cardiac muscle fibers contain an extremely high density of mitochondria (approximately 25% of cell volume), along with a rich capillary supply, enabling continuous aerobic ATP production and exceptional fatigue resistance throughout a lifetime.": "",
  "A medical student is comparing muscle biopsy slides from two athletes: a long-distance swimmer and a powerlifter. She notices the powerlifter's muscle fibers are significantly larger in diameter. What does this difference in fiber size most likely reflect?": "",
  "The powerlifter has more muscle fibers from cell division (hyperplasia)": "",
  "The two athletes have different species of muscle tissue": "",
  "The powerlifter's individual fibers have increased in size (hypertrophy) due to resistance training, adding more myofibrils per fiber": "",
  "The swimmer's fibers have degenerated from overuse": "",
  "Heavy resistance training stimulates hypertrophy, where existing muscle fibers grow larger by synthesizing additional myofibrils and myofilaments, increasing the cross-sectional area and force-generating capacity of each fiber.": "",
  "A surgeon is repairing a severed nerve to a patient's quadriceps muscle. She explains that without nerve supply, the muscle will waste away. Which component of the motor unit is damaged, and what condition will develop?": "",
  "The motor neuron is severed, and the denervated muscle fibers will undergo denervation atrophy": "",
  "The T-tubules are severed, but the muscle will function normally": "",
  "The sarcolemma is damaged, causing hypertrophy": "",
  "The epimysium is torn, causing the muscle to swell permanently": "",
  "When the motor neuron component of a motor unit is severed, the muscle fibers it innervates lose their neural stimulation and undergo denervation atrophy, progressively shrinking in size and losing function until the nerve is repaired or reinnervation occurs.": "",
  "A pharmacology student is learning about nerve agent poisoning. The instructor explains that nerve agents inhibit acetylcholinesterase, causing ACh to accumulate at the NMJ. Based on knowledge of NMJ physiology, what cascade of events would occur in the victim's muscles?": "",
  "Muscles would immediately relax and become flaccid": "",
  "ACh would accumulate, causing continuous stimulation, fasciculations, spasms, and eventually paralysis from receptor desensitization": "",
  "Only smooth muscle would be affected while skeletal muscle remains normal": "",
  "Muscles would function normally because the body would compensate": "",
  "Inhibition of acetylcholinesterase causes acetylcholine to accumulate in the synaptic cleft, leading to continuous stimulation of the motor end plate, initial muscle fasciculations and spasms, followed by depolarization block and flaccid paralysis as receptors become desensitized.": "",
  "A sports medicine physician is explaining to a young athlete why a proper warm-up is important before sprinting. She describes how T-tubules must carry action potentials deep into the muscle fiber for coordinated contraction. If T-tubules were absent, what would happen during a sprint?": "",
  "The sarcoplasmic reticulum would compensate fully for the missing T-tubules": "",
  "The muscle would contract normally because T-tubules are not essential": "",
  "Only the outer myofibrils would contract while the interior ones would not, producing weak and uncoordinated contractions": "",
  "The muscle would contract faster because signals would not need to travel through T-tubules": "",
  "Without T-tubules, the action potential would only depolarize the surface of the muscle fiber; the interior myofibrils would not receive the signal to trigger SR calcium release, resulting in weak, uncoordinated contractions because only superficial myofibrils would be activated.": ""
}